(41, 1, 28, 33, 5, 4, 4, NULL, 'Fame and Greatness Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of greatness and recognition. In Mark, Jesus'' fame spreads throughout Galilee, while Micah speaks of one who will be great unto the ends of the earth.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 1, 28, 40, 4, 24, 24, 'his fame spread abroad', 'Spread of Fame', 'This connection highlights the spread of Jesus'' fame as noted in both passages. Mark 1:28 mentions the fame spreading throughout Galilee, while Matthew 4:24 describes it extending to Syria, indicating a growing recognition of his healing powers.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 1, 28, 41, 1, 45, 45, 'his fame spread abroad', 'Spread of Jesus'' Fame', 'Both passages emphasize the spreading fame of Jesus. In Mark 1:28, his fame begins to spread, while in Mark 1:45, it has escalated to the point where he cannot enter the city openly due to the crowds drawn to him.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 1, 28, 42, 4, 17, 17, 'fame spread abroad', 'Connection of Fame and Prophecy', 'Both passages emphasize the spread of Jesus'' influence. In Mark, his fame spreads, while in Luke, he engages with prophetic scripture, indicating a growing recognition of his role.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 1, 29, 42, 4, 38, 39, 'entered into the house of Simon', 'Healing in Simon''s House', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus entering Simon''s house after leaving the synagogue. This connection highlights the immediate context of healing Simon''s mother-in-law, showcasing Jesus'' authority over illness.', 'parallel', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 1, 29, 40, 8, 14, 15, 'house of Simon and Andrew', 'Healing in Peter''s House', 'Both passages emphasize the location of Peter''s house, where Jesus performs a healing. The mention of Simon in Mark connects directly to Peter in Matthew, highlighting the continuity of events in Jesus'' ministry.', 'parallel', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 1, 29, 41, 1, 21, 21, NULL, 'Transition from Synagogue to Home', 'Both passages emphasize the movement from the synagogue to a private setting. The transition from teaching in the synagogue to entering Simon''s house illustrates the immediate aftermath of Jesus'' teaching.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 1, 29, 41, 1, 23, 23, 'entered into the house of Simon', 'Healing and Deliverance Theme', 'This connection highlights the theme of healing and deliverance present in both passages. The unclean spirit in the synagogue sets the stage for the subsequent healing actions that occur in Simon''s house.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 1, 29, 42, 9, 58, 58, 'entered into the house', 'Connection of Jesus'' Living Conditions', 'This connection highlights the contrast between Jesus'' communal life with his disciples and his lack of a permanent home. In Mark, Jesus is seen entering a house, while in Luke, he emphasizes his own lack of a place to rest.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 1, 30, 46, 9, 5, 5, NULL, 'Connection of Apostolic Authority', 'Both passages emphasize the familial relationships of apostles. Mark mentions Simon''s mother-in-law, while 1 Corinthians refers to leading about a sister, a wife, highlighting the significance of family ties among apostles.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 1, 30, 41, 5, 23, 23, 'lay sick of a fever', 'Healing and Intercession', 'Both passages emphasize the act of seeking healing for the sick. In Mark 1:30, Simon''s mother-in-law is sick, while in Mark 5:23, a father seeks healing for his dying daughter.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 1, 30, 43, 11, 3, 3, NULL, 'Connection of Sickness and Healing', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of sickness and the urgency of seeking help. In Mark, Simon''s mother-in-law is sick, prompting immediate action, while in John, the sisters send for Jesus because their brother is sick, indicating a similar urgency.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 1, 30, 59, 5, 14, 15, NULL, 'Healing and Prayer Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of healing through prayer. Mark 1:30 mentions a sick person, while James 5:14-15 instructs prayer for the sick, highlighting the communal aspect of seeking healing.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 1, 31, 44, 9, 41, 41, 'and lifted her up', 'Healing and Restoration Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the act of lifting someone up, resulting in restoration to health or life. This connection highlights the theme of miraculous healing and the subsequent service or testimony of the healed individual.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 1, 31, 19, 103, 1, 3, NULL, 'Healing and Blessing Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of healing present in both passages. Mark 1:31 describes Jesus healing Peter''s mother-in-law, while Psalms 103:3 speaks of God healing all diseases.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 1, 31, 19, 116, 12, 12, 'ministered unto them', 'Response to Divine Benefits', 'This connection highlights the theme of gratitude for divine intervention. In Mark, the healing leads to service, while Psalms expresses a desire to respond to God''s benefits.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 1, 31, 41, 5, 41, 41, 'took her by the hand', 'Healing and Resurrection Motif', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus taking someone by the hand and restoring them to health. This connection highlights the theme of Jesus'' authority over sickness and death.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 1, 31, 42, 8, 2, 3, 'ministered unto them', 'Healing and Ministry of Women', 'This connection highlights the theme of healing leading to ministry. In both passages, individuals who have been healed, like Peter''s mother-in-law and Mary Magdalene, respond by serving and ministering to Jesus and others.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
